{
  "doc_id": "26290",
  "text": "Primary systemic, neoadjuvant, or preoperative therapy is the standard of care in patients with operable and locally advanced breast cancer [CITATION_1] . Comparable outcomes have been found for pre-and post-operative administration of various cytotoxic regimens [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ; however, pre-operative therapy has the advantage of the assessment of pathological tumor response, which has been correlated with improved survival [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Additionally, it provides an opportunity to evaluate biological markers after treatment. Therefore, in this proof-of-principle study we intended to evaluate the safety and biological and clinical efficacy of the epigenetic agents hydralazine and magnesium valproate plus neoadjuvant doxorubicin and cyclophosphamide in locally advanced breast cancer.",
